+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01WrrWhTRCNnagyNcGSP7SSm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Let me design the algorithm:\n\n**Algorithm Design:**\n\nFor `countBeamCells`:\n- BFS/simulation: Start beam at source `S` going downward. Track all beams with (row, col, direction). Use a Set for visited cells. When hitting a splitter, spawn two new beams (down-left, down-right). Continue until all beams exit the grid. This is efficient since beams only go downward and the grid is finite.\n\nFor `countBeamPaths`:\n- We can't enumerate paths (2^50 is too large). Instead, use dynamic programming on splitters. Each beam segment either exits the grid (1 path) or hits a splitter (spawning 2 sub-beams). We can compute the number of paths from each splitter by finding which splitter (or exit) each of its two output beams reaches, then sum recursively with memoization. This is O(splitters^2) which is fast for 50 splitters.\n\nKey insight for paths: For each beam with a direction at a position, trace where it goes. It either exits (1 path) or hits a splitter (sum of paths from left child + paths from right child). Memoize by (splitter_index, incoming_direction) or just by the two outgoing beams from each splitter.\n\nActually, since a splitter always splits into down-left and down-right regardless of incoming direction, we just need to compute paths(splitter) = paths_from(down-left beam) + paths_from(down-right beam), where paths_from(beam) traces the beam in its direction until it either exits (returns 1n) or hits another splitter (returns paths(that_splitter)). Memoize per splitter."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":259,"cache_read_input_tokens":20194,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":259},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_u